  - TOOL_CALL: create_or_update_file({"file_path": "expert_knowledge_v2.txt", "content": "## Expert Knowledge for Fuzzing Build Failures - SharpYUV Specific\n\n### Current Status:\n1. **Progress Made**: Successfully resolved 3 out of 4 missing libraries: `-lbrotlidec`, `-lbrotlicommon`, `-lbz2`\n2. **Remaining Issue**: `-lsharpyuv` library still missing despite installing `libwebp-dev`\n3. **Build Stage**: Compilation succeeded 100%, main library `libgdal.a` built successfully, linking fails at fuzzer building stage\n\n### SharpYUV Library Analysis:\n1. **SharpYUV Background**: SharpYUV is a YUV image processing library part of the WebP ecosystem, introduced in newer versions of libwebp.\n2. **Ubuntu 20.04 Issue**: The base image uses Ubuntu 20.04 with libwebp version 0.6.1, which may not include SharpYUV support or the library may be named differently.\n3. **Library Naming**: The library file might be named differently (e.g., `libsharpyuv.so` vs `libwebp.so` containing SharpYUV symbols).\n\n### Investigation Strategies:\n1. **Check Installed Files**: Verify what files were installed with `libwebp-dev` package.\n2. **Library Search**: Look for SharpYUV symbols in existing WebP libraries.\n3. **Version Requirements**: Determine if GDAL requires a newer WebP version with SharpYUV support.\n4. **Build from Source**: Consider building WebP from source to get SharpYUV support.\n\n### Diagnostic Commands:\n1. `dpkg -L libwebp-dev` - List files installed by libwebp-dev package\n2. `find /usr -name \"*sharpyuv*\" -o -name \"*webp*\"` - Search for SharpYUV related files\n3. `nm -D /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libwebp.so | grep -i sharpyuv` - Check for SharpYUV symbols in libwebp\n4. `apt-cache show libwebp-dev` - Check package version and details\n\n### Potential Solutions:\n1. **Install Different Package**: Look for `libsharpyuv-dev` or similar package (may not exist in Ubuntu 20.04).\n2. **Build WebP from Source**: Download and build newer WebP version with SharpYUV support.\n3. **Linker Flag Adjustment**: Use `-lwebp` instead of `-lsharpyuv` if symbols are in main WebP library.\n4. **Symbol Renaming**: Check if SharpYUV functions have different names in older WebP versions.\n5. **Disable Feature**: If possible, configure GDAL to not use SharpYUV features.\n\n### Common Pitfalls:\n1. **Version Mismatch**: GDAL may expect newer WebP API than available in Ubuntu 20.04.\n2. **Symbol Visibility**: SharpYUV symbols might be in `libwebp` but not exported with expected names.\n3. **Build Configuration**: GDAL's CMake configuration may need adjustment for older WebP versions.\n4. **Dependency Chain**: Other libraries (like poppler) may also have WebP dependencies causing conflicts.\n\n### Recommended Approach:\n1. First diagnose what WebP version is installed and what SharpYUV components exist.\n2. Check GDAL's CMake configuration for WebP/SharpYUV detection.\n3. Consider building WebP from source if missing functionality.\n4. As last resort, patch GDAL to not require SharpYUV or use alternative implementation."})
